		<div id="content">				<h1 class="pagetitle">Basic OCR correction</h1>
		<div class="entry page clear">
			<p><strong>by Ted Underwood and Loretta Auvil</strong></p>
<p>Although optical character recognition is imperfect, we can often address the worst of the imperfections. The simplest approach is to develop a set of rules to translate individual tokens produced by OCR errors back into correctly-spelled forms.</p>
<p>Obviously, this approach has limits. You can&#8217;t anticipate all the possible errors. Worse, you can&#8217;t anticipate all possible correct words. It&#8217;s always possible that you&#8217;ll correct &#8220;Defist&#8221; to &#8220;Desist,&#8221; when it was in this one case the name of a French nobleman.</p>
<p><a href="https://usesofscale.files.wordpress.com/2012/10/smellie.png"><img data-attachment-id="60" data-permalink="https://usesofscale.com/gritty-details/basic-ocr-correction/smellie/" data-orig-file="https://usesofscale.files.wordpress.com/2012/10/smellie.png" data-orig-size="355,257" data-comments-opened="1" data-image-meta="{&quot;aperture&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;credit&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;camera&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;caption&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;created_timestamp&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;copyright&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;focal_length&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;iso&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;shutter_speed&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;title&quot;:&quot;&quot;}" data-image-title="Smellie" data-image-description="" data-medium-file="https://usesofscale.files.wordpress.com/2012/10/smellie.png?w=300&#038;h=217" data-large-file="https://usesofscale.files.wordpress.com/2012/10/smellie.png?w=355" src="https://usesofscale.files.wordpress.com/2012/10/smellie.png?w=300&#038;h=217" alt="" title="Smellie" width="300" height="217" class="alignright size-medium wp-image-60" srcset="https://usesofscale.files.wordpress.com/2012/10/smellie.png?w=300&amp;h=217 300w, https://usesofscale.files.wordpress.com/2012/10/smellie.png?w=150&amp;h=109 150w, https://usesofscale.files.wordpress.com/2012/10/smellie.png 355w" sizes="(max-width: 300px) 100vw, 300px" /></a>However, with all that said, the practical reality is that many OCR errors are quite predictable. Especially in the period 1700-1820, errors often fall into predictable patterns of substitution produced by archaic typography or worn and broken type (s -&gt; f, h -&gt; li, h -&gt; b, e -&gt; c, sh -&gt; m). Moreover, the predictable errors are the ones we really need to care about. Rare, random errors aren&#8217;t going to distort data mining significantly, but a systematic substitution of f for s, limited to a particular span of years, is a problem we have to address!</p>
<p>So it&#8217;s possible, and useful, to produce a pretty-good list of rules that simply translate individual tokens back into correctly spelled words. Here&#8217;s <a href="https://dl.dropbox.com/u/4713959/BestLcOCRRules.txt" target="_blank">one such initial list,</a> containing 50,000 translation rules produced by Ted Underwood and Loretta Auvil, specifically for the period 1700-1899.</p>
<p><a href="https://usesofscale.files.wordpress.com/2012/10/ocr.jpg"><img data-attachment-id="118" data-permalink="https://usesofscale.com/gritty-details/basic-ocr-correction/ocr-2/" data-orig-file="https://usesofscale.files.wordpress.com/2012/10/ocr.jpg?w=497" data-orig-size="297,134" data-comments-opened="1" data-image-meta="{&quot;aperture&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;credit&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;camera&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;caption&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;created_timestamp&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;copyright&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;focal_length&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;iso&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;shutter_speed&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;title&quot;:&quot;&quot;}" data-image-title="OCR" data-image-description="" data-medium-file="https://usesofscale.files.wordpress.com/2012/10/ocr.jpg?w=497?w=297" data-large-file="https://usesofscale.files.wordpress.com/2012/10/ocr.jpg?w=497?w=297" src="https://usesofscale.files.wordpress.com/2012/10/ocr.jpg?w=497" alt="OCR"   class="alignright size-full wp-image-118" srcset="https://usesofscale.files.wordpress.com/2012/10/ocr.jpg 297w, https://usesofscale.files.wordpress.com/2012/10/ocr.jpg?w=150 150w" sizes="(max-width: 297px) 100vw, 297px" /></a>We identified a set of predictable character substitutions and used the Google ngrams dataset as a source of common OCR errors. In cases where a limited number of predictable substitutions translated a common error back into one (and only one) dictionary word, we accepted that translation as a &#8220;correction rule.&#8221; In this list the rules are sorted by frequency, and the third column represents a number of occurrences.</p>
<p>Please note that this list is specific to the period 1700-1899. If you use it on twentieth-century texts, you might end up &#8220;correcting&#8221; some modern acronyms. Also, this list is designed to normalize everything to British modern spelling; if you want to preserve differences between American and British spelling, you&#8217;ll need a different approach.</p>
<p>Finally, there are <a href="https://dl.dropbox.com/u/4713959/AmbiguousPairs.txt" target="_blank">many pairs of words,</a> like &#8220;six/fix&#8221; or &#8220;soul/foul,&#8221; where a likely OCR error is also a correctly spelled word. In situations like this, no list of 1gram rules will be adequate. Instead, you need a contextual spellchecking algorithm. Since &#8220;immortal soul&#8221; is a more probable phrase than &#8220;immortal foul,&#8221; context can help us correct words that a mere dictionary check would accept.</p>
<p>Underwood is about to generate a larger list of 1-gram rules using a more flexible probabilistic approach. We also have an algorithm for contextual spellchecking (&#8220;immortal foul&#8221; -&gt; &#8220;immortal soul&#8221;). But neither of those resources is quite ready for prime time yet. So we&#8217;re providing <a href="https://dl.dropbox.com/u/4713959/BestLcOCRRules.txt" target="_blank">this initial list of 50,000 rules</a> as a temporary stopgap solution for people interested in correcting 18th and 19th-century OCR.</p>
<div id="jp-post-flair" class="sharedaddy sd-like-enabled sd-sharing-enabled"><div class="sharedaddy sd-sharing-enabled"><div class="robots-nocontent sd-block sd-social sd-social-icon-text sd-sharing"><h3 class="sd-title">Share this:</h3><div class="sd-content"><ul><li class="share-twitter"><a rel="nofollow" data-shared="sharing-twitter-54" class="share-twitter sd-button share-icon" href="https://usesofscale.com/gritty-details/basic-ocr-correction/?share=twitter" target="_blank" title="Click to share on Twitter"><span>Twitter</span></a></li><li class="share-facebook"><a rel="nofollow" data-shared="sharing-facebook-54" class="share-facebook sd-button share-icon" href="https://usesofscale.com/gritty-details/basic-ocr-correction/?share=facebook" target="_blank" title="Share on Facebook"><span>Facebook</span></a></li><li class="share-end"></li></ul></div></div></div><div class='sharedaddy sd-block sd-like jetpack-likes-widget-wrapper jetpack-likes-widget-unloaded' id='like-post-wrapper-41540578-54-592087367813e' data-src='//widgets.wp.com/likes/#blog_id=41540578&amp;post_id=54&amp;origin=usesofscale.wordpress.com&amp;obj_id=41540578-54-592087367813e' data-name='like-post-frame-41540578-54-592087367813e'><h3 class='sd-title'>Like this:</h3><div class='likes-widget-placeholder post-likes-widget-placeholder' style='height: 55px;'><span class='button'><span>Like</span></span> <span class="loading">Loading...</span></div><span class='sd-text-color'></span><a class='sd-link-color'></a></div></div>								</div><!--end entry-->
